Product name: 1960's VANITY CASE / Weekend Case / School Bag: In Dark Grey by Antler of Birmingham England
Description:
A 1960's weekend bag in Dark Gray by Antler of Birmingham England; world renouned manufacturers of quality Suitcases, travel bags hand bags etc. 
( visit: www.antler.co.uk )
Whilst (adult) Ladies in the 1960's used this type of bag with a leather covered handle and leatherette covered sturdy sides, top and base as an overnight bag or bag for all their cosetics and pampering lotions and potions, I remember differently! 
A craze caught on, certainly in York England where I was born and educated. All the 'incrowd' High School (Secondary School) teenage girls used these exact same bags (and cheeper replicas) as school bags. There was plenty of room for pens, pencils, ruler, & eraser, gym kit & pumps (plimsoles), homework books, packed lunch, magazines, ingredients for the Domestic Science (cookery) lesson and a little illicit makeup and/or a few cigarettes and matches!!
This bag has all the indications of possible High School use with a pen (biro/bic mark on the inside lid, a few stains on the inside and what looks like cracking and a  repair to the leather at one end of the handle. The handle remains strong and usable despite its appearance in photograph 5!! 
Having given the minor negatives, the Vanity Case is in remakably good condition with:
* no splits, no tears or cuts, no unravelling stitching etc in the leatherette. 
* a lid that fits as it should and the hinges work as originally intended. 
* a locking mechanism that closes nicely and in a firm manner
* a key which seems to operate the lock (more often than not) ..... but
   which, I don't think, it is the original!
* an interior with all the elasticated 'garter' holders and concealed  
   pocke in place with no tears.
* an internal base still covered by the original protective, clear vinyl,
   wipe  clean, liner
This is a genuine Antler Weekend / Vanity Case with the Antler logo on the front and an Antler tag secreted inside the back storeage pocket. 
The Antler Vanity Cases also had, and this one has, off set handle fixing points and shot satin/silk interiors.
The case measures 
12.75" wide (left to right)
9.5" deep (Front to back)
7" tall and
5.25" to the top of the handle loop.

Product name: Vintage SiLK NiSHiJiN ORi KINCHaKU - for 7-5-3-Ceremony - FREE SHiPPiNG!!!
Description:
This is a vintage silk kinchaku. It would be a darling bag for a small one, a special bag for you to keep something in, or even great as display!
A kinchaku is a drawstring pouch which is carried when wearing a kimono to carry your necessities. This one is particular would be for a very young child for the ceremony which is called 'shichi-go-san' in Japanese. Literally means 7-5-3, and children whos ages are 7, 5 or 3 celebrate by going to temple, and they dress up, go to temple to get blessed.
Thus, the very shiny and fancy silk, which is a type of silk brocade called Nishijin Ori, from Kyoto. These brocades are reknowned for their fine patterns and use of gold and silver and other special threads. The Nishijin district has been hit especially hard after the Kobe earthquake of 1997, many of the small factories have had to shut down, and the industry is at a crisis.
So unfortunately, the beautiful brocades will eventually become harder and harder to find.
here's a Wikipedia page about Nishiujin Ori silks.
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nishijin
This Nishijin kinchaku is in great condition. It is from the sixties, central japan. A name has been penned into the lining silk, 'Kiku', and slightly bled thru the silk to the outside layer, but it is really hardly noticeable.
Will send in the regular airmail. Should be about 2 weeks.
FREE SHIPPING!!!!! It's included in the price.
thanx fer lookin'!

Once you buy eight or more, they come in a flat-rate priority envelope.
Buyers, do NOT put these little works of art into the washer or dryer. They are so delicate they will shred.  Unfortunately, I cannot replace them if you wash them in this way.  Hand wash with gentle soap that has been diluted in a basin of warm (but not hot) tap water and air dry, flat.  Take great care when ironing them, also. They can take a hot iron if you are very gentle about moving the iron around the handkerchief, and use absolutely NO steam.  I cannot be responsible for these once you launder them. They are 50 to 100 years old. They have been carried in ladies' pockets from the days of WWII to now.  Why would you throw them in a load with your bluejeans?  
Attention brides:  These are first quality handkerchiefs suitable as gifts. I have sifted through collections of handkerchiefs and have weeded out all the ones that are torn, stained, full of holes or otherwise no good. I cannot discount them for batch sales of 100 or more.  I have seen them sell here in California for 10.00 apiece. My prices are very competitive, so please don't ask about buying them for 1.00 apiece.  Occasionally I can put together a set of 100 with tiny flaws and sell them for 99.00. I call those listings Bride on a Budget.   Congratulations!

This listing is for 2 ounces (57 g) of solid organic lanolin. The lanolin comes in a metal tin (yay for no plastic!). This is pharmaceutical grade, organic, pure lanolin. This 100% Lanolin is manufactured from the wool of free range sheep raised in Australia.
Lanolin can be used for a number of things, but here I will highlight its importance in wool diaper covers and the most green way of cloth diapering: wool. 
In order to perform to their highest potential, your wool cloth diaper covers and soakers will need to be lanolized. This should take place every 1-2 months, depending on how frequently you use your wool item, and if you're using them overnight or during the day. 
When your cover is retaining a urine odor, it is time to wash it. If you prefer to lanolize every time you wash, you can do so. I prefer to lanolize every few washings.

https://www.etsy.com/listing/129584225/lanolin-soap-for-wool-care-organic?

Description:
Now presenting my newest Edition.....Organic Extra Strength Deodorant! 
Made with all Organic Ingredients that help to eliminate odor causing bacteria with our own blend of Organic Essential Oils! It is Free of Corn Starch and instead we use Tapioca Starch! Corn starch contains natural sugars that feed odor causing bacteria. Using Tapioca Starch instead helps to keep you feeling dry just like Corn Starch, without accelerating the life of common under arm bacteria!
Most Natural Deodorants are made with a high concentration of Coconut Oil which does not stand up well to the Summer heat, or for traveling!  We have blended Organic Extra Virgin Coconut Oil, which has its own properties, with Organic Unrefined Beeswax AND Organic Unrefined Cocoa Butter which helps harden it up! Unrefined ingredients contain all of the natural vitamins and enzymes that help your skin!
♦After becoming aware of the dangers of Anti-Perspirants, I started formulating my OWN Organic Deodorant! I used Anti-Perspirant up until about 5 years ago when I gave Organic Deodorant a try! I was wary as I did not want to go around smelling of "Onion Rings", BUT did not want to continue using the chemical & metal infused deodorant on the store shelves! 
It took a few days for my body to adjust to it, but soon my under arms became adjusted to it and I no longer had any lingering odor!
♦Facts About Anti-Perspirants and Why you should make the switch!
~Anti-Perspirants use micronized Aluminum that clogs your sweat glands preventing them from sweating.
~Aluminum DOES occur naturally in the world as a common mineral, BUT is not safe to have lodged in your pores!
~Your under arm area is also where some of your Lymph Nodes are located! They are very important for filtering impurities from your system. How can they filter your normal environmental toxins if they are bogged down with chemicals?
I recommend giving it at least a week of daily use to get your body accustomed to a chemical free deodorant. My testers have reported wonderful results!

Sweet almond oil is a favorite in aromatherapy as a carrier oil and is valued in natural skin care for it's ability to soften and condition the skin. Pale yellow in color, almond oil is expeller pressed from raw almond kernels. The oil contains glucosides, minerals and vitamins and is rich in protein. Almond oil is good for all skin types and helps to relieve dryness, itching and inflammation.
Almonds are a rich source of Vitamin E, and mono unsaturated fat, one of the two "good" fats responsible for lowering LDL cholesterol. Almond nuts are a healthy treat as is, or can be made into almond butter, a spread similar to peanut butter.
Finely ground almonds also serve as an organic exfoliating ingredient in facial skin scrubs. The gentle abrasive action of the almonds helps to remove dead skin cells, and are the perfect natural replacement for facial soap.

Product name: Procion MX Dye, Turquoise, the most vivid of all dyes for cellulose (natural) fibers by Jacquard
Description:
Procion MX Dye, Turquoise, the most vivid of all dyes for cellulose (natural) fibers by Jacquard.  Cold water fiber dye
Use this dye for immersion dyeing, tie dye, batik, airbrushing, garment dyeing, screen printing, spatter painting gradation dyeing and more! Powder solution changes color when adding water. Final result matches bottle label. 
This cold water dyes does not require heat. This unique property sets Procion MX apart from all other dyes and establishes them as the undisputed king of backyard dyeing, batik and tie dye. 
Because Procion MX dyes can be used away from the stovetop, they are also perfect for shibori, ice dyeing, tub and low water immersion dyeing, printing, direct painting and other “alternative” dye applications.
 As a fiber reactive dye, Procion MX forms a strong covalent bond with cellulosic fibers, making it the most permanent and washfast of all dyestuffs. Examples of Fabric/Fiber
Ccellulose fibers: cotton, linen, canvas hemp, jute, ramie, sisal, paper, rayon and more. May also be used with protein fibers if acidified.
 Mix the concentrated dye powder with warm tap water to create the most vibrant of all colors for cotton, linen and other plant-based fabrics. Procion MX dyes are typically used with a soda ash fixative, which can be added directly to the dye bath or used to pre-treat the fabric, as in tie dyeing.
- Typically, one 2/3 oz/19 g bottle will dye more than 1 lb/0.45 kg of dry fabric. 
(Very bright colors will require more dye and pastel colors will require less.)
Available in a variety of colors, each sold separately. Conforms to ASTM D 4236. Made in USA.

Product name: Cross Stitch Patterns -- Wash Your Hands 5x7 (5 versions) and bonus Wash Your Hands patterned for bathroom towel (2 versions)
Description:
Cross stitch patterns "Wash Your Hands" 5x7 (in 5 different versions) and for bathroom towel or horizontal bookmark (in 2 versions). PDF digital download.
---The Story---
This is NOT a finished cross stitch. 
This listing is for a PDF pattern for several "Wash Your Hands" patterns depicting different common microbes. They are intermediate to advanced level patterns, but each can be finished easily in an afternoon.
By request, there are now several versions of the 5x7 "Wash Your Hands" pattern available (which will also fit on huck style hand towels with a 5x7 stitchable area), with the third microbe being switched out for several different options: the original ironic mad cow disease; cholera; black plague; C. Diff; and common cold, also shown in the longer horizontal towel pattern.
Any of the microbes shown in any of these patterns may also be stitched individually for a 3" round embroidery hoop, though several of them are augmented from the originals for use in the "Wash Your Hands" pattern. 
---The Deets---
*WHAT YOU NEED: To complete these patterns, you will need knowledge of basic cross stitch, back-stitching, half stitches and filler stitches as well as French knots in some cases. The completed stitches were originally designed to fit on specific types of towels, but the first one (with E. Coli) can also fit in a 5x7 frame when stitched on regular 14 ct Aida cloth.
*WHAT YOU WILL GET: You will NOT receive a physical product. The patterns and images can be downloaded as soon as your payment has gone through, here on Etsy. Please let me know if you have any trouble opening or receiving the files!
The pattern includes a color legend for DMC embroidery floss.
*HOW YOU WILL GET IT: You will NOT receive a physical product. You will be able to download the files after payment has gone through. If you have any trouble, email or convo me and let me know!
If you would like a kit containing all the materials needed to complete the 5x7 "Wash Your Hands" in any of its several versions, it's up in the shop! See "The Links" below.

Product name: Sajou Fil au Chinois "Lin Cable" Waxed Linen Thread #332 (0.77mm) in 31 colors/Saddlery Thread/Corded Thread/Linen Cable/Thread for Leather
Description:
♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦ FOR SALE ♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦
Brand new Sajou Fil au Chinois "Lin Cable" Waxed Linen Thread #332 (0.77mm diameter). 31 colors. Made in France
♦ Thread is not on a spool. You will get winded to cardboard and placed to protective plastic bag thread. 
The #332 linen cable is the thickest thread in the range with a diameter of 0.77mm. Each spool contains 50 grams, about 133 meters of thread. These threads are twisted when damp, which avoids the linen fiber from being altered during twisting. Cabling or cording is a twisting of two already-twisted threads.
♦♦♦♦♦ About Fil au Chinois "Lin Cable" waxed linen thread: ♦♦♦♦♦
The Fil Au Chinois waxed “Lin Cable” is a luxury thread for high-quality leather work. As indicated in the name, this thread is cabled, signifying that the threads have been twisted a first time, and then these threads are assembled and twisted a second time. The term "cable", or corded, signifies this double twist. This obviously increases greatly the solidity of the thread, but also makes it more rounded, particularly adaptable for leather work. We have five thicknesses of linen cable: N°332 (0.77mm diameter), N°432 (0.63mm diameter), N°532 (0.57mm diameter), N°632 (0.51mm diameter), and N°832 (0.43mm diameter).
To order simply choose the color and quantity you want from the list.
♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦ SAJOU FIL AU CHINOIS ♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦♦
The name, fil au Chinois, dates back to a period in France when anything Oriental was fashionable. This interest for the Orient became very popular with the expedition to Egypt in 1798, by Bonaparte (the future Napoléon), Algeria’s conquest by France (1830) and twenty-five years later the opening up of China and Japan only reinforced this interest. The beginning of the brand Au Chinois was at the heart of this cultural movement. The idea was a success as it permitted the creation of a character easily identifiable and now legendary.
The brand, Fil Au Chinois was registered in 1847, by Francois-Philibert Vrau who founded his company in Lille twenty years beforehand. This was to protect an innovative method to present threads; spools surrounded with a label and placed in boxes.
But the brand Fil au Chinois really took off in the 1850’s with the arrival of Philibert Vrau, the director’s son. 
Then, like many other brands in Northern France, the Fil Au Chinois had a long period of decline mainly due to the first domestic sewing machines which were unsuitable for linen threads, industrial difficulties, inappropriate commercial policies...
While production numbers for the Fil Au Chinois didn’t stop decreasing, the interest for publicity objects and old products only increased for seasoned collectors. 
The Fil Au Chinois thread could have been in danger of disappearing had it not been for two, determined industrialists, Olivier and Bruno Toulemonde.In charge of Ets Toulemonde, one of the last remaining French thread manufacturers, the two brothers realized the importance of reviving and prolonging the history of Fil Au Chinois.
In 2007, Olivier and Bruno Toulemonde, determined to revive Fil Au Chinois and bring it back to its former glory, bought the branded product having overcome various difficulties amongst them putting machines back into working order, some dating back to 1890.
Frédérique Crestin-Billet, a passionate collector and herself at the heart of the Sajou brand revival, is part of this joint venture to restore the quality packaging that was once the hallmark of Fil Au Chinois.
